explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_MutSemDelete are dead code you must know which operations have observable side effects and which only affect local values. Each listed symbol is needed for that analysis:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines the return_code used by the if-condition and may perform side effects (token initialization, starting transactions). Needed to know when the if-block executes and whether GetById itself has effects that would be lost if removed.
- OS_MutSemDelete_Impl: The call inside the if-block may perform resource/state changes (actual semaphore deletion). Required to know if removing that call would change program behavior.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Performs the common finalize steps (may commit/cancel transactions, notify, free resources). Required to see whether its removal would alter behavior beyond a mere return-code assignment.
- OS_object_token_t: Type/layout of token passed between the routines — needed to understand what data is conveyed and whether token initialization by GetById or use by other calls has side effects.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success value tested by the if — needed to determine branching and whether code inside the if is reachable/conditional.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Argument passed to GetById that affects which object is looked up; influences whether GetById succeeds and thus whether the if-block runs.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE: Argument passed to GetById that can change GetById semantics/side effects (e.g., lock acquisition) and therefore whether removal changes behavior.
- osal_id_t: Type of sem_id (caller-visible ID) — needed to reason about value ranges/semantics that affect GetById outcome.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: If GetById or Finalize use transaction init semantics, the transaction init behavior (side effects/time) matters to determine if removal changes observable behavior.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Transaction cancel semantics may be invoked on error paths; needed to see side effects that Finalize/Delete sequences cause.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Finalizer may call this; required to assess commit/finalization side effects that would be lost if the finalizer were removed.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used (indirectly via Impl) to map token to object index and may produce side effects or rely on token contents — needed to fully understand Impl behavior.
- OS_NotifyEvent: FinalizeDelete may notify other subsystems (events) — notifications are observable side effects; required to determine if removing the call would change program behavior.

Including these symbols lets the next analyst see whether any assignment or function call within OS_MutSemDelete has only local effects (dead) or produces observable/global effects (not dead).
